<zyHTML id="15bf41f7-9809-aa42-dbf7-b302d5b5d69e" caption="">
<p>Below is a simple program that includes an expression involving integers. </p>
</zyHTML>


<zyVersion version="java">
<zyFigure caption="Expressions examples: Leasing cost." id="ebaf62c9-c4d6-8b3c-c1fc-908c47bad829" type="CodeConsole">
<zyCode language="java" highlight="25"> 
import java.util.Scanner;

/* Computes the total cost of leasing a car given the down payment,
   monthly rate, and number of months 
*/

public class CarLeaseCost {
   public static void main(String[] args) {
      Scanner scnr = new Scanner(System.in);
      int downPayment; 
      int paymentPerMonth; 
      int numMonths;
      int totalCost; // Computed total cost to be output

        
      System.out.print("Enter down payment: ");
      downPayment = scnr.nextInt();

      System.out.print("Enter monthly payment: ");
      paymentPerMonth = scnr.nextInt();

      System.out.print("Enter number of months: ");
      numMonths = scnr.nextInt();
        
      totalCost = downPayment + (paymentPerMonth * numMonths);
        
      System.out.println("Total cost: " + totalCost);
   }
}
</zyCode>
<zyConsole>
Enter down payment: 500
Enter monthly payment: 300
Enter number of months: 60
Total cost: 18500
</zyConsole>
</zyFigure>
</zyVersion>



<zyQSetTF caption="Simple program with an arithmetic expression. " id="ce5b2199-5041-424e-b30d-f08625478c11">
<p>Consider the example above. </p>

<zyQ>
<zyQText correct="Yes" truelabel="Yes" falselabel="No">Would removing the parentheses as below have yielded the same result?<br />
<zyCode nobox="true">downPayment + paymentPerMonth * numMonths;</zyCode></zyQText>
<zyQExpl>The * would still be evaluated first, because * has higher precedence than +. But using parentheses makes the programmer's intent more clear to people reading the program.  
</zyQExpl>
</zyQ>

<zyQ>
<zyQText correct="Yes" truelabel="Yes" falselabel="No">Would using two assignment statements as below have yielded the same result? Assume this declaration exists: int totalMonthly<br />
<zyCode nobox="true">totalMonthly = paymentPerMonth * numMonths;
totalCost = downPayment + totalMonthly;</zyCode></zyQText>
<zyQExpl>The evaluation is ultimately the same, yielding the same result. Breaking larger expressions into multiple assignments with smaller expressions can sometimes improve code readability.   </zyQExpl>
</zyQ>
</zyQSetTF>



<zyHTML id="785996a2-1284-5e9d-18b4-14d30bad0744" subsection="true" caption="Style: Single space around operators">
<h3>Style: Single space around operators</h3>
</zyHTML>


<zyHTML id="f94a9f4e-c194-40cf-9018-fda472721d1e">
<p><zyGoodPractice id="31a01d8c-5125-6e7f-06e5-6178616f1a21"> A good practice is to include a single space around operators for readability, as in numItems + 2, rather than numItems+2.</zyGoodPractice> An exception is minus used as negative, as in: xCoord = -yCoord. <zyDefn> Minus (-) used as negative is known as _unary minus_.</zyDefn></p>
</zyHTML>



<zyQSetShortAnswer caption="Single space around operators." id="569ddcd8-8ec8-16fa-946f-ab14541694f3">
<p>Retype each statement to follow the good practice of a single space around operators. </p>
<p>Note: If an answer is marked wrong, something differs in the spacing, spelling, capitalization, etc. This activity emphasizes the importance of such details.</p>

<zyQ>
<zyQText><zyICode>housesCity = housesBlock *10; </zyICode></zyQText>
<zyQAns columns="30"  obeycase="true" obeyspace="true">housesCity = housesBlock * 10;</zyQAns>
<zyQHint>Add single space before and after *. Make sure there are no extra spaces before or after the statement itself, e.g. spaces after the semicolon.</zyQHint>
<zyQExpl>The spaces ensure the operator is clearly visible. Note that a semicolon (;) is not an operator and should not be preceded by a space.</zyQExpl>
</zyQ>

<zyQ>
<zyQText><zyICode>tot = num1+num2+2;</zyICode></zyQText>
<zyQAns columns="30"  obeycase="true" obeyspace="true">tot = num1 + num2 + 2;</zyQAns>
<zyQHint>Add single space before and after each +.</zyQHint>
<zyQExpl>The spaces reduce human reader confusion with num2 and 2.</zyQExpl>
</zyQ>

<zyQ>
<zyQText><zyICode>numBalls=numBalls+1;</zyICode></zyQText>
<zyQAns columns="30"  obeycase="true" obeyspace="true">numBalls = numBalls + 1;</zyQAns>
<zyQHint>Add single space before and after the +, AND the =.</zyQHint>
<zyQExpl>The spaces around the = ensure the assignment is clearly visible.</zyQExpl>
</zyQ>

<zyQ>
<zyQText><zyICode>numEntries = (userVal+1)*2;</zyICode></zyQText>
<zyQAns columns="30"  obeycase="true" obeyspace="true">numEntries = (userVal + 1) * 2;</zyQAns>
<zyQHint>Add single space before and after the +, AND the *. Don't forget the space before the *.</zyQHint>
<zyQExpl>The spaces may lead to more readable expressions.</zyQExpl>
</zyQ>
</zyQSetShortAnswer>



<zyHTML id="22da8f5c-1eac-39e0-8479-ea2672b6c64c" subsection="true" caption="Compound operators">
<h3>Compound operators</h3>
</zyHTML>


<zyHTML id="3b327643-f985-c655-aae0-c75c27bcbcb8" caption="Compound operators">
<p><zyDefn>Special operators called _compound operators_ provide  a shorthand way to update a variable, such as userAge _+=_ 1 being shorthand for userAge = userAge + 1. Other compound operators include _-=_, _*=_, _/=_, and _%=_. </zyDefn></p>  
</zyHTML>



<zyQSetShortAnswer caption="Compound operators." id="38e59b70-eb95-fe73-1cba-cd4b6bdba171">
<zyQ>
<zyQtext>numAtoms is initially 7. What is numAtoms after: numAtoms += 5?  </zyQtext>
<zyQans>12</zyQans>
<zyQhint>Same as numAtoms = numAtoms + 5. </zyQhint>
<zyQexpl>Same as numAtoms = numAtoms + 5, so 7 + 5 is 12. </zyQexpl>
</zyQ>

<zyQ>
<zyQtext>numAtoms is initially 7. What is numAtoms after: numAtoms *= 2?  </zyQtext>
<zyQans honeypot="true">     14     </zyQans>
<zyQhint>Same as numAtoms = numAtoms * 2. </zyQhint>
<zyQexpl>Same as numAtoms = numAtoms  * 2, so 7 * 2 is 14. </zyQexpl>
</zyQ>

<zyQ>
<zyQtext>Rewrite the statement using only a compound operator. If the statement can't be rewritten using only a compound operator, type: Not possible<br/><br/>
<zyICode>carCount = carCount / 2;</zyICode></zyQtext>
<zyQans obeycase="true">carCount /= 2;</zyQans>
<zyQhint>carCount /= ?;</zyQhint>
<zyQexpl>carCount /= 2 is same as carCount = carCount / 2. </zyQexpl>
</zyQ>

<zyQ>
<zyQtext>Rewrite the statement using only a compound operator.  If the statement can't be rewritten using only a compound operator, type: Not possible<br/><br/>
<zyICode>numItems = boxCount + 1;</zyICode></zyQtext>
<zyQans>Not possible</zyQans>
<zyQhint>Compound operator requires: var = var + 1, where var is the same variable. But the variables are not the same on both sides of the =.   </zyQhint>
<zyQexpl> A compound operator is shorthand for when a variable is being updated, not for a more general assignment. Both sides must thus have the same variable, but here the variables are different (numItems and boxCount). </zyQexpl>
</zyQ>
</zyQSetShortAnswer> 



<zyHTML id="fd1b4e4e-0cfd-12bd-42db-167a4f1ec74e" subsection="true" caption="No commas allowed">
<h3>No commas allowed</h3>
</zyHTML>


<zyHTML id="97e18b25-feea-43c7-8034-836830dc8056">
<p>Commas are not allowed in an integer literal. So 1,333,555 is written as 1333555.</p> 
</zyHTML>



<zyQSetTF caption="Expression in statements." id="8b3566db-8096-4cf4-806b-a4d065e81bdf">
<zyQ>
<zyQText correct="Yes" truelabel="Yes" falselabel="No">Is the following an error? Suppose an int's maximum value is 2,147,483,647.<br/>
<zyCode nobox="true">int numYears;
numYears = 1,999,999,999;</zyCode></zyQText>
<zyQExpl>Commas aren't allowed in an integer literal. The correct statement is <zyICode>numYears = 1999999999;</zyICode>

</zyQExpl>
</zyQ>
</zyQSetTF>

